@article{Rosenbaum1983e,
abstract = {{Income diversification and food security among rural households in Nigeria Muhammad Sani Muhammad (GS 33000) Supervisory Committee Prof (Dr) Mohammed Mansor B. Ismail (Chairman) Prof (Dr) Mad Nasir B HJ Shamsudin (Member) Associate Prof (Dr) Amin Mahir Bin Abdullah (Member) INTRODUCTION The major challenge facing most developing countries is how to achieve the millennium development goal number one, which is the eradication of hunger and poverty by 2015. Although still of central importance in household income, agriculture on its own is increasingly unable to provide sufficient means of survival and livelihood to rural dwellers, especially in sub-Saharan Africa. Agriculture has undoubtedly become the most important sub-sector in the Nigerian economy next only to petroleum. The sector employs about 70 percent of the workforce while accounting for slightly more than 40 percent of Gross Domestic Product (GDP), Central Bank of Nigeria and United State Agency for International Development (CBN, 2008; USAID, 2013). Recent evidences suggest that farming income alone is unable to cater for the entire needs of rural households [Ellis, 1998; 1999]. This is why the farmers are still looking for diverse opportunities to increase and stabilize their incomes and consumption [Chapman and Tripp, 2004]. Babatunde (2009; Ibekwe, et al., 2012) reported that, farming households in Northern Nigeria often pursue different non-agricultural activities simultaneously or at different times throughout the year. Traditionally, rural income is equated with farm or agricultural income, but very few households derive the entire source of their livelihood from agriculture. Literature converge that on the average, roughly 40 percent of African rural household income on average being derived from non-farm source (Ellis 1999; Babatunde, 2006). PROBLEM STATEMENT In spite of the key roles NFIGA played in uplifting the general wellbeing and livelihoods of rural people in developing economies and providing about 40\% of rural total income, studies that explore the impact of non-farm sector on the food consumption expenditure are still scanty. Most studies on non-farm diversification in developing countries tend to focus more on the causes, patterns and determinants less attention is accorded to the actual impacts of such strategies on the real gains in food security and the general wellbeing of the rural households. Likewise, many studies adopted OLS and non-probability regression models that do not account for the selection bias. To fill in this knowledge gap, the current study seeks not only to assess the predictors of non-farm diversification, but also to determine the potential impacts of NFIGA on real food expenditure and food security of rural households in Nigeria using 2010 post-planting GHS-panel data. The study is meant to build on the existing knowledge on the non-farm income diversification on food security and the wellbeing of rural households in Nigeria. The study used PSM technique which is capable of taking care of selection bias and as the most commonly being used in many current impact studies in education, agriculture and many social and medical sciences. LITERATURE REVIEW There are a number of motives that influence the decision by rural household to diversify their portfolios away from agriculture to off-farm and other non-farm activities. Babatunde, 2008 argued that, shrinking land availability is among the main reasons for the growing role of off-farm income among farm households in developing countries. Ellis (1998; 1999 \& Ahmed, 2012) also reported that, households diversified their portfolios to avert poverty, food insecurity, risk considerations; consumption smoothing, labour allocation smoothing, credit market failures and shock coping strategies. Several studies in Nigeria reported a substantial and increasing share of both off-farm and non-farm income in the total household income. For example Babatunde and Qaim, (2010) reported that 65 per cent small-holder farmers households participated in off-farm employment in which 50 per cent of their total income comes from off-farm activities. A number of recent articles examine aspects of income diversification using different case studies in Nigeria to provide empirical evidence (Legg et al., 2005,Nasa’i, 2010, Adewunmiet al., 2011). METODOLOGY In recent years, PSM is the most commonly used technique in non-experimental causal studies to evaluate the impact of a particular intervention or participation in a particular program that addresses the issue of selection bias. Propensity score matching has recently been used in several studies to evaluate the impacts of different programs related to agriculture, poverty and food security. For example, Becker and Inchino (2002; Owusu et al, 2011). The propensity score can be calculated by averaging the conditional effects over propensity score distribution of diversified households as follows: $\Delta$│E=1=Ep(x)\{E(Y1i│P(Xi), Ei=1)-E(Y0i│P(Xi),Ei=0)\}│Ei=1\}\ldots\ldots\ldots\ldots\ldots\ldots..(1) RESULTS AND DISCUSSION This study reveals an increase in food expenditure due to participation in NFIGA, the average treatment effects on treated ATT of N1571.52 to N11654.07 were obtained using nearest neighbour and radius matching techniques (see table 1). The mean food expenditure due to participation in non-farm income generating activities as was computed N11071.48 that is (N66142.86 minus N55071.38) based on the sample size before estimating PSM. Therefore, estimation of counterfactuals with complete sample underestimates the impact NFIGA diversification by N654.07. The two basic assumptions (confoundedness and common support) were all satisfied by the model. Table 1: Impact of non-farm income generating activities on household food expenditure (N) Matching Method Treatment Control Difference Std Error T-Test Nearest neighbor Unmatched 64605.07 52825.30 11779.76 2082.46 5.66*** ATT 64613.08 63041.