abstract = {In this paper, we define vulnerability as the probability that a household will experience a future period of poverty. This sort of dynamic concern has behavioral implications separate from those of poverty. As a consequence, a measure that identifies vulnerable households is potentially quite valuable. This paper suggests such a measure. We apply two versions of our measure to a comprehensive panel from rural Pakistan. One relies on an assumption of normally distributed shocks to expenditure. The other involves sampling from the empirical distribution. We test each measure by comparing its predictions to the actual outcomes observed in the panel. To conclude, we suggest an extension of our measure to the case of repeated cross-sections.},
