abstract = {The most original feature of the French Fifth Republic is the use of a two-round system for both presidential and legislative elections. This article considers the effects of this electoral system and its development in the first 50 years of the Republic. It distinguishes between two types of effects: mechanical and psychological. It reviews the theoretical arguments for each and the available evidence. The authors first specify a series of vote-seat curves that characterise the mechanical effect, paying particular attention to the mediating effects of coalitions. They then examine the psychological effect through a series of tests on coalition formation. The article concludes by noting that much remains to be learned about the electoral system and its effects in the French Fifth Republic.},
